<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920127-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>920127-0063.</DOCID><HL>   Owner of Penny Stock   Brokerage Firm Pleads   Guilty of Racketeering</HL><DATE>01/27/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9C</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>INSIDER TRADING (ISD)SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEWARK, N.J. -- The owner and president of a defunct NewYork penny stock brokerage firm pleaded guilty toracketeering and fraud in a scheme to manipulate at leastthree penny stocks.   Leo M. Eisenberg, 70 years old, was charged withracketeering, stock manipulation, bribery and insidertrading. He admitted to using Monarch Funding Corp., aManhattan brokerage firm he owned from 1965 to 1990, as aracketeering enterprise from 1982 to 1989.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Eisenberg pleaded guilty to the first count of a 1989indictment that charged him and two other men withracketeering in connection with fraudulent trading in thepenny stocks of at least six companies, including LiquidationControl Inc., Toxic Waste Containment Inc. of Washington andHigh Technology Capital Corp. of Paterson, N.J.   Mr. Eisenberg, formerly of Woodmere, N.Y., who now livesin upstate New York and Boca Raton, Fla., has agreed tocooperate with the authorities, and is free on $850,000 bail.   Mr. Eisenberg faces a maximum of 20 years in federalprison and fines ranging from $250,000 to twice the profit orloss due to the scheme, which have been estimated in themillions of dollars. Barry M. Fallick, Mr. Eisenberg'slawyer, declined to comment.   Richard O. Bertoli, 59, and Richard S. Cannistraro, 39,were also charged along with Mr. Eisenberg, and have beenindicted again by a Newark federal grand jury forracketeering in the same penny stock fraud schemes thatnetted more than $7 million in profit for Messrs. Bertoli,Cannistraro and Eisenberg. Mr. Eisenberg, who has not beenindicted again, has said Mr. Bertoli masterminded theschemes.   Mr. Cannistraro, a former securities analyst who iscurrently in jail for securities fraud, and Mr. Bertoli,former president of defunct Executive Securities Corp., NewYork, allegedly along with Mr. Eisenberg prepared falseresearch reports on the six companies, and traded thecompanies' stock based on advance knowledge of the reports.The indictment also alleges that the defendants bribed twoportfolio managers and a New York securities analyst to gettheir companies to buy large blocks of the six companies'stock.</TEXT></DOC>